<section id="sec.rpminst">
  <title id="title.rpminst">&sr; Installation from RPMs (Linux)</title>

  <section>
    <title>Introduction</title>

    <para>
      Three RPMs, providing different capabilites, exist for each
      supported Linux distribution:
      <itemizedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>The &sr;/BioPSE RPM includes the BioPSE package.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>The &sr;/Fusion RPM includes the Fusion and DataIO packages
	  and HDF5 libraries.  The version of &sr; in the &sr;/Fusion
	  RPM has been configured to use MDSplus software but MDSplus
	  software must be installed separately.  See <xref
	  linkend="sec.mdsplus_inst"/> for  MDSplus software
	  installation instructions.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para> The &sr;/Insight RPM includes the Insight and TEEM
	  packages and Insight libraries.</para>
	</listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
      The version of &sr; included in all RPMs has been configured
      to support BLAS but BLAS libraries must be installed
      separately.  See <xref linkend="sec.blas_lapack_inst"/> for BLAS
      installation instructions<footnote><para>BLAS/ATLAS and LAPACK are often
    pre-installed in Linux distributions.</para></footnote>.
    </para>

    <para>
      Root privileges are required to install the &sr;
      <acronym>RPM</acronym>s.
    </para>

    <para>
      The following procedure installs &sr; in
      <filename>/usr/local/&sr;/bin</filename>.
    </para>

    <para>
      RPM installation consists of the following steps:
      <orderedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Downloading the &sr; RPM distribution and &sr;'s sample data
	  sets.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Installing &sr; using the <command>rpm</command> command.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Installing &sr;'s sample data sets.</para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>Installing &sr;'s documentation.</para>
	</listitem>
      </orderedlist>
    </para>

  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Downloading</title>
    <para>
      From <acronym>SCI</acronym>'s <ulink
      url="http://software.sci.utah.edu/archive_entry.html">software
      archive</ulink> page download the following files:

      <itemizedlist>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    <filename>&sr;-<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>-<replaceable>system</replaceable>.rpm</filename>
	    <replaceable>System</replaceable> is the Linux distribution of interest.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    <filename>SCIRunData.<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>.tar.gz</filename>
	    (or
	    <filename>FusionData.<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>.tar.gz</filename>
	    if also downloading the Fusion specific RPM).
	  </para>
	</listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <para>
	    <filename>docs.<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>.tar.gz</filename>
	  </para>
	</listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
    </para>

  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Installing</title>

    <para> Start a terminal (e.g. xterm) application.  Become the root
    user by typing:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
su -	
      </literallayout>
      Command <command>su</command> prompts for root's password.</para>
      <para>
	Install the RPM by typing:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
rpm -ivh &sr;-<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>-<replaceable>system</replaceable>.rpm
      </literallayout>
      </para>
      <para>The RPM should take approximately one minute to
      install.</para>
    <para>
      Type <command>exit</command> to leave the root account.
    </para>
    <para>
      &sr; can be removed using the <command>rpm</command> command:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
	rpm -e &sr;
      </literallayout>
      Read  <xref
      linkend="sec.prepare"/> before
      <link linkend="sec.starting">starting</link> &sr;.
    </para>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>&sr;'s Sample Data Sets</title>
    <para>
      Install
      the sample data sets into
      <filename>/usr/local</filename>.
    </para>
    <para>
      Become root:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
	su -
      </literallayout>
      and type:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
	gunzip -c SCIRunData.<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>.tar.gz | (cd /usr/local &amp;&amp; tar xf -)
      </literallayout>
      This will create <filename>/usr/local/&sr;Data</filename>, the
      sample data sets directory.  Type <command>exit</command> to leave the
      root account.
    </para>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>&sr;'s Documentation</title>
    <para>
      The following procedure installs the documentation
      in the directory <filename>/usr/local</filename>
    </para>
    <para>
      Use the <command>su</command> command to become the root user.  Then
      <command>cd</command> to the directory containing the compressed
      documentation tarball and type:
      <literallayout class="monospaced">
	gunzip -c SCIRunDocs.<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>.tar.gz | (cd /usr/local &amp;&amp; tar xf -)
      </literallayout>
      This will create <filename>/usr/local/&sr;Docs.<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable></filename>, the
      &sr; documentation directory. Type <command>exit</command> to leave the
      root account.
    </para>
    <para>
      Open <filename>/usr/local/&sr;Docs.<replaceable>x.x.x</replaceable>/doc/index.html</filename>
      with a web browser to view &sr;'s online documentation.
    </para>
  </section>

</section>
